2.2 Belief Update

An important property of trust is that subjects often ‚Äòcome
around‚Äô to trusting another person or entity. In other words,
trust in a WS must be updated using past experiences ‚Äì both
positive and negative. As trust is derived from the belief,
B(pi; a, b), we must develop a way to update the belief with past experiences of users with the WS i.
After n interactions with WS i, let there be r positive experiences and s non-positive (possibly negative) experiences, where n = r + s. We wish to update the prior belief, B(pi; a, b), with these experiences resulting in an updated belief, B (pi| r, s ). Notice that the probability of a positive experience is pi, and that of a non-positive experience is (1‚àípi). Given the experiences, we may update the belief over pi in a Bayesian manner:

