3 Predictors of Positive Experience
Our trust model is based on the conÔ¨Ådence in the probability of having a positive experience with a WS i, which is updated using the number of positive and other types of experiences with the WS. Unlike previous efforts [9, 16], we hypothesize what is meant by an ‚Äòexperience‚Äô with i. Although experiences tend to be subjective, the variables we provide are meant to serve as predictors of likely positive experiences. These predictors are not exhaustive and others may also exist.
While interacting with a WS, a user may consider the competency, reliability and honesty of the service. We deÔ¨Åne an experience as:

DeÔ¨Ånition 4 (Experience). Experience of a user with a WS, i, is the behavior of i in terms of its competency, reliability and honesty.

‚Ä¢ Competency: ability of the service to perform all the necessary actions to achieve a particular goal. ‚Ä¢ Reliability: ability of the service to provide the same desired output upon repeated invocations without any discrepancy. ‚Ä¢ Honesty: ability of the service to be faithful to terms agreed upon in the service level agreement and other contracts.
We may expect experiences of users with a WS to be pos-
itive if the WS is competent, reliable and honest. Therefore,
we brieÔ¨Çy discuss how we may objectively ascertain these
characteristics of WSs. We may measure honesty of a service as the difference be-
tween the advertised or agreed upon values of QoS parameters appearing in the service level agreements and the actual observed values of the QoS parameters. As cost is not observed, we limit our focus to the parameters, response time R¬Ø and availability A. The response times are normalized, as we show below, to make them comparable with availability. Let Aa and R¬Øa be the advertised values while Am and R¬Øm be the observed values of the QoS parameters. Then, we deÔ¨Åne an objective measure of honesty, h ‚àà [0, 1], as:

h

=

1

